SIMPLE: lodge
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lodge
<hw>Lodge</hw> <pr>(l⟦ocr⟧j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>loge</ets>, <ets>logge</ets>, F. <ets>loge</ets>, LL.
<ets>laubia</ets> porch, gallery, fr. OHG. <ets>louba</ets>, G.
<ets>laube</ets>, arbor, bower, fr. <ets>lab</ets> foliage. See
<er>Leaf</er>, and cf. <er>Lobby</er>, <er>Loggia</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A shelter in which one may rest;</def>
<specif>as:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A shed; a rude cabin; a hut;
<as>as, an Indian's <ex>lodge</ex></as>.</def> <au>Chaucer.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their <qex>lodges</qex> and their tentis up they gan bigge [to
build].</q> <rj><qau>Robert of Brunne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O for a <qex>lodge</qex> in some vast wilderness!</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A small dwelling house, as for a gamekeeper or
gatekeeper of an estate.</def> <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A den or
cave.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The meeting room of an association; hence,
the regularly constituted body of members which meets there; <as>as, a
masonic <ex>lodge</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The chamber of an
abbot, prior, or head of a college.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The space at the mouth of a
level next the shaft, widened to permit wagons to pass, or ore to be
deposited for hoisting; -- called also <altname>platt</altname>.</def>
<rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A collection of objects lodged together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Maldives, a famous <qex>lodge</qex> of islands.</q>
<rj><qau>De Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A family of North American Indians, or the persons
who usually occupy an Indian lodge, -- as a unit of enumeration,
reckoned from four to six persons; <as>as, the tribe consists of about
two hundred <ex>lodges</ex>, that is, of about a thousand
individuals</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lodge gate</b></col>, <cd>a park gate, or entrance gate,
near the lodge. See <er>Lodge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 1
<sd>(b)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lodge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lodge
<hw>Lodge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Lodged</conjf> <pr>(l⟦ocr⟧jd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lodging</conjf> <pr>(l⟦ocr⟧j"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To rest or remain a lodge house, or other shelter; to rest; to
stay; to abide; esp., to sleep at night; <as>as, to <ex>lodge</ex> in
York Street</as>.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stay and <qex>lodge</qex> by me this night.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Something holy <qex>lodges</qex> in that breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fall or lie down, as grass or grain, when
overgrown or beaten down by the wind.</def>
<rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To come to a rest; to stop and remain; to become
stuck or caught; <as>as, the bullet <ex>lodged</ex> in the bark of a
tree; a piece of meat <ex>lodged</ex> in his throat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lodge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lodge
<hw>Lodge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>loggen</ets>, OF.
<ets>logier</ets>, F. <ets>loger</ets>. See <er>Lodge</er>,
<pos>n.</pos> ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To give shelter or rest to;
especially, to furnish a sleeping place for; to harbor; to shelter;
hence, to receive; to hold.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every house was proud to <qex>lodge</qex> a knight.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The memory can <qex>lodge</qex> a greater store of images than all
the senses can present at one time.</q> <rj><qau>Cheyne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To drive to shelter; to track to covert.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The deer is <qex>lodged</qex>; I have tracked her to her
covert.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deposit for keeping or preservation; <as>as, the
men <ex>lodged</ex> their arms in the arsenal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to stop or rest in; to implant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>lodged</qex> an arrow in a tender breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To lay down; to prostrate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though bladed corn be <qex>lodged</qex>, and trees blown down.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To present or bring (information, a complaint)
before a court or other authority; <as>as, to <ex>lodge</ex> a
complaint</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To lodge an information</b></col>, <cd>to enter a formal
complaint.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lodgeable</ent>⟦br⟧
